@NODE "Description"
@NEXT "Requirements"
@PREV "Main"
@TOC "Main"

TeSty is just another program for styling the text, you know, MaKiNG it
l00k çŘřŁ. Its work is based on the character tables, so TeSty is able to do
anything you can made a table for. TeSty has 6 internal tables for styling
English letters and has the ability to use external tables, supposing they
have a special format. This version includes total of 22 tables (hence the
version is 1.0.22), but you may easily make some of your own. For example,
this is how the internal "all 2 lower" table made: this table converts all
English letters to lower case. First four bytes should be "TSTY", this is
a token, by which TeSty recognizes its table. Next two bytes are the
starting and ending chars of the range to be converted. All chars that are
out of this range will be copied without any change. In this example only
chars between $41 (A) and $5A (Z) will be converted to lowercase (converting
other chars to themselves makes no sense, anyway). After these two bytes
the destination chars should follow, taken as follows: if you intend to
place 'a' instead of 'A', you find the code of 'A' ($41) and put 'a' to its
place, and so on. The amount of this chars should be exactly (ending
char)-(starting char). Right after the last char you should put the
null-terminated name of the table you made, maximum 54 chars long (e.g.
"all 2 lower"), and then a short description of it, also null-terminated
and max. 54 chars ("Makes all characters lowercase").

If you made a table, and want it to be included with the next version of
Testy, just send it to me by @{" e-mail " LINK "Author"}.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requirements"
@NEXT "Installation"
@PREV "Description"
@TOC "Main"

You will need an Amiga computer with OS 3.0+ (not tested on lower
versions).


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installation"
@NEXT "Usage"
@PREV "Requirements"
@TOC "Main"

Just copy it anywhere you like.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage"
@NEXT "Author"
@PREV "Installation"
@TOC "Main"

The 'TableInfo' and 'Comment' fields, obviously, contain infromation about the
current table.
The 'Style' cycle-button allows to select one of the internal tables.
The 'String' checkmark activates converting of string instead of file (see
below).
The 'Table' button allows you to select an external table, which path and
name will be shown in the stringgadget besides.
The '<-' button clears the stringgadget with table's name and path.
The 'Infile' and 'Outfile' buttons allow you to select a file to convert
and a name for destination (converted) file.
The 'Instring' and 'Outstring' stringgadgets allow you to convert a string
up to 54 chars, if 'String' checkmark is set. You can paste a text from
clipboard to 'Instring' with PowerSnap, NewEdit, MCP or something alike, or
enter it manually, and then get the converted string from 'Outstring'.
The 'Start Conversion' button should be pressed to begin the conversion of
a file or string. While conversion is in progress, all the input to the
window will be locked and pointer will be changes to 'busy' state. This
won't take much time, though, as converting routine is written in asm.


@ENDNODE


